00:12:48.859 --> 00:12:53.059
to just have, let's say, a large EC2 instance started.

00:12:53.059 --> 00:12:54.739
Now we could just, literally for us,

00:12:54.739 --> 00:12:58.340
we could just start it ourselves.

00:12:58.340 --> 00:13:00.460
So something like this, I already have a few of them

00:13:00.460 --> 00:13:01.840
at the bottom, like four of them.

00:13:01.840 --> 00:13:07.140
So just for me to get started, the test, that was super easy.

00:13:07.140 --> 00:13:08.979
And it really provided familiar tooling

00:13:08.979 --> 00:13:11.659
on the cloud with the flexibility between R, Python,

00:13:11.659 --> 00:13:13.059
and Linux.

00:13:13.059 --> 00:13:16.219
The reason why that was huge is because for us,

00:13:16.219 --> 00:13:20.179
even though we do most of our tooling in R,

00:13:20.179 --> 00:13:21.900
many of the bioinformatics workflows

00:13:21.900 --> 00:13:23.859
that we have actually exist as packages

00:13:23.859 --> 00:13:26.419
that you need Linux to start.

00:13:26.419 --> 00:13:29.200
And so just like any other IDE, having this available

00:13:29.200 --> 00:13:31.020
was super helpful for us.

00:13:31.020 --> 00:13:31.940
And it's on the cloud.

00:13:31.940 --> 00:13:34.380
So for example, now I can go around

00:13:34.380 --> 00:13:37.159
with my MacBook Air, which doesn't really

00:13:37.159 --> 00:13:39.599
have a lot of memory, but then be able to work everything

00:13:39.599 --> 00:13:42.080
there as well.

00:13:42.080 --> 00:13:44.320
So I'm going to go through three use cases.

00:13:44.320 --> 00:13:47.419
The first use case, how this has really impacted us,

00:13:47.419 --> 00:13:49.880
is expediting clinical trials and publications.

00:13:49.880 --> 00:13:56.479
Having close to 30-plus or so publications, it's a lot.

00:13:56.479 --> 00:13:58.679
But the reason why we were able to get there

00:13:58.679 --> 00:14:01.159
is because of this workflow.

00:14:01.159 --> 00:14:05.000
So we essentially are able to put all of our pipelines

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:09.599
onto RStudio, be able to run it pretty much

00:14:09.599 --> 00:14:12.799
as just a general run.

00:14:12.799 --> 00:14:16.039
And then essentially, we use R Markdown,

00:14:16.039 --> 00:14:18.280
where it's kind of shown there how

00:14:18.280 --> 00:14:21.080
we can deliver a lot of this to our academic partners.

00:14:21.080 --> 00:14:25.239
From those HTMLs that they have, they can literally choose,

00:14:25.239 --> 00:14:28.440
OK, these are interesting that we could publish on,

00:14:28.440 --> 00:14:30.280
create the figures, and then essentially it

00:14:30.280 --> 00:14:32.760
goes back into just publishing.

00:14:32.760 --> 00:14:34.400
So those are actually three papers

00:14:34.400 --> 00:14:37.159
that we got, I think, the last few months or so.

00:14:40.679 --> 00:14:43.479
Use case number two, it saved us almost a year

00:14:43.479 --> 00:14:44.640
of product development.

00:14:44.640 --> 00:14:48.200
And the reason why is because a lot of our methodologies,

00:14:48.200 --> 00:14:50.359
I talked only about biological age,

00:14:50.359 --> 00:14:52.080
but we can actually use DNA methylation

00:14:52.080 --> 00:14:55.880
to look at essentially your lab values, CRP, HbA1c,

00:14:55.880 --> 00:14:59.960
a whole slew of metabolites, a whole slew of proteins

00:14:59.960 --> 00:15:02.200
that are estimated from DNA methylation.

00:15:02.200 --> 00:15:03.280
For those of you that are interested,

00:15:03.280 --> 00:15:04.359
please talk to me after.

00:15:04.359 --> 00:15:06.400
I'd be happy to explain how that's working.

00:15:06.400 --> 00:15:08.760
But essentially, if you think about it from an ML

00:15:08.760 --> 00:15:12.799
perspective, you are training an individual model

00:15:12.799 --> 00:15:15.799
for each and every one of those metabolites, proteins,

00:15:15.799 --> 00:15:17.320
and clinical values.

00:15:17.320 --> 00:15:19.239
And so for that, we actually, this

00:15:19.239 --> 00:15:22.320
was part of a preprint that we published earlier,

00:15:22.320 --> 00:15:24.760
and now we're submitting to Nature Medicine.

00:15:24.760 --> 00:15:27.880
But essentially, it's about 1,700 models

00:15:27.880 --> 00:15:30.799
that we were able to whittle down from a total of 5,000

00:15:30.799 --> 00:15:33.080
after validation, clinical validation.

00:15:33.080 --> 00:15:39.000
And now we're able to sell that to the consumer with almost

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:41.880
a $90, for $90, essentially.

00:15:41.880 --> 00:15:43.400
So you're able to get all of this.

00:15:43.400 --> 00:15:46.479
Now, we're not Theranos.

00:15:46.479 --> 00:15:47.919
I swear to God.

00:15:47.919 --> 00:15:49.679
The reason why, again, we're not Theranos

00:15:49.679 --> 00:15:52.200
is because that academic publication

00:15:52.200 --> 00:15:56.760
is where we really want to make sure that what can we say

00:15:56.760 --> 00:15:58.039
and what cannot we say.

00:15:58.039 --> 00:16:00.799
And that's where it really allows us for, especially

00:16:00.799 --> 00:16:05.679
for use case number one, where that's been very helpful there.

00:16:05.679 --> 00:16:08.880
And so we can offer these as reports, essentially.

00:16:08.880 --> 00:16:11.359
And use case number three is, within the organization,

00:16:11.359 --> 00:16:13.719
we have a lot of, let's just say,

00:16:13.719 --> 00:16:15.640
non-engineers and non-bioinformaticians

00:16:15.640 --> 00:16:17.159
who are part of the company.

00:16:17.159 --> 00:16:18.479
But we need to empower them to be

00:16:18.479 --> 00:16:21.479
able to essentially show and sell these products.

00:16:21.479 --> 00:16:28.320
Because again, because of the state of biomedical research,

00:16:28.320 --> 00:16:31.919
it's really hard to educate the masses on this.

00:16:31.919 --> 00:16:33.479
And so for them, they need to have

00:16:33.479 --> 00:16:36.299
a quick way of showing the associations to disease,

00:16:36.299 --> 00:16:38.880
how you could use this, what is the information that you could

00:16:38.880 --> 00:16:41.479
really leverage, especially with this new science.

00:16:41.479 --> 00:16:43.239
So that's been really helpful.

00:16:43.239 --> 00:16:45.119
So a shout out to Laura on our team,

00:16:45.119 --> 00:16:49.280
who's actually developed a shiny tool for data visualization.

00:16:49.320 --> 00:16:50.919
Essentially taking all of our data

00:16:50.919 --> 00:16:54.440
from the over 50,000 individuals who have taken our tests

00:16:54.440 --> 00:16:57.039
and be able to show that to the rest of the,

00:16:57.039 --> 00:17:02.280
when explaining our science.

00:17:02.280 --> 00:17:03.880
So what are we excited about?

00:17:03.880 --> 00:17:07.760
I got a really shout out to Nick, Posit Marketing, and Tom,

00:17:07.760 --> 00:17:11.239
Posit Engineering, and the two engineers I talked to.

00:17:11.239 --> 00:17:14.939
DataBot and Posit Workbench, I'm super excited about.

00:17:14.939 --> 00:17:16.560
The reason why this is really important

00:17:16.560 --> 00:17:17.979
is because on the left side, these

00:17:17.979 --> 00:17:22.359
are fixed HTMLs that need a lot of human interaction

00:17:22.359 --> 00:17:26.640
to create, a.k.a., they don't really let me out much.

00:17:26.640 --> 00:17:29.160
I'm usually in the basement coding away.

00:17:29.160 --> 00:17:31.640
But instead of doing that, why not

00:17:31.640 --> 00:17:34.079
use something like Anthropic Cloud Coding

00:17:34.079 --> 00:17:39.760
and also just try to use some AI tools to kind of glean

00:17:39.760 --> 00:17:42.119
a little bit more from the data.

00:17:42.119 --> 00:17:44.359
So that's where we're really excited about.

00:17:44.359 --> 00:17:46.920
That's already sent a couple of messages

00:17:46.920 --> 00:17:50.199
to our bioinformatics team and engineering team for that.

00:17:50.199 --> 00:17:53.000
And so, yeah, I think with that said, thank you,

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:55.119
especially to everyone, especially the Posit team,

00:17:55.119 --> 00:17:56.880
for everything you guys do.

00:17:56.880 --> 00:17:59.560
You've really made our lives a bunch easier.

00:17:59.560 --> 00:18:02.160
And for anyone else who's interested in the science

00:18:02.160 --> 00:18:04.359
aspect, we'd love to collaborate.

00:18:04.359 --> 00:18:05.760
Especially right now, we're looking

00:18:05.760 --> 00:18:08.520
for ways to create R packages that we can give out

00:18:08.520 --> 00:18:10.079
to the rest of the community, mainly

00:18:10.079 --> 00:18:14.079
because this is the Wild West, especially for epigenetics.

00:18:14.280 --> 00:18:18.959
So if you have any interest in that or helping us out,

00:18:18.959 --> 00:18:23.239
my LinkedIn and email, I use my email like I'm texting.

00:18:23.239 --> 00:18:25.760
So yeah, I'm always on there.

00:18:25.760 --> 00:18:28.199
So thank you, and happy to take questions.

00:18:28.199 --> 00:18:32.640
All right, thank you, Varun.

00:18:32.640 --> 00:18:33.599
Great presentation.

00:18:33.599 --> 00:18:34.640
Yeah, thanks.

00:18:34.640 --> 00:18:36.880
So we have time for maybe one or two questions.

00:18:36.880 --> 00:18:40.160
The first question, I don't understand.

00:18:40.160 --> 00:18:44.199
It is, DNA methanolination is highly tissue dependent.

00:18:44.199 --> 00:18:46.479
How does the blood test correlate with the tissue test

00:18:46.479 --> 00:18:48.280
for assessing tissue age?

00:18:48.280 --> 00:18:48.920
Perfect.

00:18:48.920 --> 00:18:50.160
Yeah, that's a great question.

00:18:50.160 --> 00:18:52.959
So yeah, it is very much tissue dependent.

00:18:52.959 --> 00:18:55.439
The way that we're looking at it is a blood test, obviously.

00:18:55.439 --> 00:18:59.160
And blood is heterogeneous in the cell mixtures.

00:18:59.160 --> 00:19:02.640
The way that we've been able to leverage kidney health

00:19:02.640 --> 00:19:05.239
or, let's say, brain health and all of that

00:19:05.239 --> 00:19:07.959
is we're looking at, if you think about blood

00:19:07.959 --> 00:19:11.319
as a systemic organ, it's capturing

00:19:11.319 --> 00:19:15.479
a lot of the signals that is part of many of your organs

00:19:15.479 --> 00:19:16.420
within your body.

00:19:16.420 --> 00:19:18.760
And so what we're using is we're using machine learning,

00:19:18.760 --> 00:19:20.800
essentially, as a way to pick out those signals.

00:19:20.800 --> 00:19:23.479
And it's very much a signal to noise ratio.

00:19:23.479 --> 00:19:25.880
So there's a paper that came out, actually,

00:19:25.880 --> 00:19:27.880
in Nature Aging about two days ago

00:19:27.880 --> 00:19:30.800
called Systems Age from our collaborators at Yale.

00:19:30.800 --> 00:19:33.000
And it actually goes through exactly how

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:35.520
we're able to deconvolute from the blood

00:19:35.520 --> 00:19:39.000
down to individual organs.

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:39.839
Amazing stuff.

00:19:39.839 --> 00:19:40.400
Cool, yeah.

00:19:40.400 --> 00:19:41.160
All right.

00:19:41.160 --> 00:19:41.640
Thank you.

